rs within a string.\n \nExample 1:\nInput: s = \"0110\", n = 3\nOutput: true\nExample 2:\nInput: s = \"0110\", n = 4\nOutput: false\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= s.length <= 1000\ns[i] is either '0' or '1'.\n1 <= n <= 109\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def queryString(self, s: str, n: int) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def queryString(self, s: str, n: int) -> bool:\n        # Check if the binary representation of each number in the range [1, n] is a substring of s\n        for i in range(1, n + 1):\n            binary_rep = bin(i)[2:]  # Get binary representation of i, excluding the '0b' prefix\n            if binary_rep not in s:\n                return False\n        return True\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through each integer from 1 to `n`, converts it to its binary representation (without the '0b' prefix), and checks if this binary string is a substring of the given string `s`. If any binary representation is not found in `s`, it returns `False`. If all are found, it returns `True`.", "estimated_date": 1553385600000}